text.tspan: Each of these properties is a reference to a section of the binary body of the Feature Table. This
section contains the data of an array with the actual property values. The data type of the array
elements is given by the type of the property. The length of the array is determined by the
The positions of the instances, given as cartesian x, y, and z coordinates. The positions can be stored directly in a
POSITION attribute, or using a compressed, quantized representation in the POSITIONS_QUANTIZED attribute.
The Feature Table of an Instanced 3D Model may contain the following properties:
The orientation of each instance can be defined with two vectors: one vector defining the up-direction, and one
vector defining the right direction. These normals can be stored in the NORMAL_UP and NORMAL_RIGHT attribute, or
using a compressed, oct-encoded representation of the normals, where the normals are stored in the
Further information about the quantized position and oct-encoded normal representations, about the
concept of relative-to-center positions, and the WGS84 ellipsoid, can be found in Section 13, "Common
The number of instances that will be rendered, stored in the INSTANCES_LENGTH property. This determines the length
of the arrays that store the per-instance properties. It also determines the size of the Batch Table in the case that the
Batch Table stores metadata for each instance.
The center point for relative-to-center positions, can be stored in the RTC_CENTER attribute. When it is defined, then
the positions are given relative to this point.
The volume that is used for quantization when the positions are given in their compressed form in the
POSITIONS_QUANTIZED property. The volume is defined by the QUANTIZED_VOLUME_OFFSET, which defines the offset
of the volume, and the QUANTIZED_VOLUME_SCALE, which defines the scale for the quantized volume.
The following tables summarize the properties that may be contained in the Feature Table of Instanced
The scaling factors for the instances. The scaling for each instance can either be a uniform scaling, which is a single
value stored in the SCALE attribute, or scaling factors along the x, y, and z-axes, given via the SCALE_NON_UNIFORM
An identifier for each instance, stored in the BATCH_ID attribute. This batch ID serves as an index that can be used
to look up properties for each instance in the Batch Table.
When the orientation is not given for the individual instances, then the EAST_NORTH_UP can be used to indicate
that each instance will default to the east/north/up reference frame's orientation on the WGS84 ellipsoid.
The offset of the quantized volume in x, y, and z-direction
The scale of the quantized volume in x, y, and z-direction
Whether the instance orientation should default to the east/north/up reference
The center position when positions are defined relative-to-center
The x,y, and z coordinates for the position of the instance
A unit vector defining the up-direction of the instance
A unit vector defining the right-direction of the instance
A scaling factor for all axes of the instance
The scaling factors for the x, y, and z-axis of the instance
The batch ID, to look up metadata for the instance in the batch table
